:: changeworld
Fair enough. Let’s start with something small. Take a look at this chart.

 <img src="img/edited_SeaIce.png" width="90%">
This chart shows the amount of Arctic Sea Ice that exists, over time, in 'millions of square kilometers'. In the Arctic, the sea water freezes and thaws naturally, over the course of a single year. 

Because of Climate Change, however, the total amount of ice is melting more and more, as the years go by. You can see the years going by at the bottom of the chart. They go up in 8’s. 

For reference, just one million square kilometers is the size of four United Kingdoms! The Arctic Sea Ice started at //seven// million square kilometers. Take a second to think about how much ice that could be, and what it would look like. 

It is certainly a lot of ice.

[[How can we show years, using music?|activity_start]]

:: activity_start
Find this set of keys on the piano. They’re the same ones from earlier.

<img src="img/C4_Eb4_F4.png" width="90%">

Play all the keys at the same time, with your left hand. This is called a ‘chord’.
<<linkreplace "Tap to continue." t8n>>
The first year on the chart is 1976. 

 <img src="img/edited_SeaIce.png" width="90%">

Practice reading the chart from left to right, and playing your chord, every time you reach a year marker, on the grid. First, play the chord to represent 1976. Then, again for 1984. Then, again, for the rest of the years. 

 As you’re playing the years, in the back of your mind, motice where the line on the graph spikes, and flattens. Think about how this line might fit alongside the years.

